	<Language_en_US>
		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_UNIT_TBM">
			<Text>Tunnel Boring Machine</Text>
		</Row>
		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_UNIT_TBM_HELP">
			<Text>Builds tunnels on mountain tiles and is consumed in the process.</Text>
		</Row>
		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_UNIT_TBM_TEXT">
			<Text>The Tunnel Boring Machine (TBM) revolutionized the process of constructing tunnels through rock and soil. Developed during the 19th century, the early versions of TBMs significantly reduced the time and labor required for tunnel construction. The first successful application of a TBM was in the construction of the Hoosac Tunnel in Massachusetts, completed in 1875. This machine, designed by Charles Wilson, proved the concept viable by excavating through challenging terrain that manual laborers struggled with.[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]Throughout the 20th century, TBMs underwent significant advancements, incorporating better materials and engineering techniques. The breakthrough in the 1950s and 1960s came with the introduction of the shielded TBM, which provided support to the surrounding ground while excavating. This innovation enabled the construction of longer and deeper tunnels, facilitating major infrastructure projects like the Channel Tunnel between the United Kingdom and France, completed in 1994.[NEWLINE][NEWLINE]Modern TBMs are sophisticated and massive machines, often custom-built for specific projects. They can bore through various types of ground conditions, from hard rock to soft soil, and are equipped with systems for soil removal and structural support installation. The use of TBMs has expanded beyond traditional rail and road tunnels to include applications in water supply, sewage, and even urban transit systems. These machines have become indispensable tools in modern civil engineering, making large-scale underground construction projects faster, safer, and more efficient.</Text>
		</Row>
		<Row Tag="TXT_KEY_UNIT_TBM_STRATEGY">
			<Text>This unit constructs tunnels through mountains, thereby improving transit times and allowing railroad connections through the empire.</Text>
		</Row>

